\i Introduction
\i0 \
Climate change is causing phenological shifts at highly variable rates across species in different functional groups and trophic levels. Such species-specific variation in response to climate change is leading to changes in the relative timing of key activities (phenological synchrony) among interacting species (REF; Kharouba et al.). These changes in synchrony have led to fitness consequences for the consumer and have influenced ecosystem-level properties in some contexts (REF) but not others (REFS). It remains difficult to anticipate what the biological importance of shifts in synchrony will be. Indeed, to date, there has been no quantitative assessments of the overall consequences across systems. \
\
Here, we focus on consumer-resource interactions and argue that there is a disconnect between ecological and evolutionary theory and understanding the consequences of climate change-driven shifts in synchrony. Better tests of theory and estimations of pre-climate change baselines will be necessary to move from documenting impacts of climate change to predicting the consequences of climate change on communities. \
\

\i Current approach\

\i0 On the topic of trophic synchrony, there has been work on i) documenting how climate change is affecting the timing of a trophic interaction; ii) how those changes in synchrony have affected consumer (less frequently resource) fitness (hereafter called \'91applied studies\'92); and iii) advancing the theory necessary to predict long-term demographic changes due to changes in synchrony (hereafter called \'91theory studies\'92). The ultimate goal of both of these studies is to predict the impacts of climate change on ecological communities. There are also studies that aim to understand the underlying processes related to timing (e.g, coevolution, life history trade offs, food web dynamics) that drive consumer or resource dynamics (hereafter called \'91fundamental studies\'92), independently of climate change. Combined, these studies have improved our understanding of the importance of the relative timing of an interaction for consumer fitness. \
\
The ecological theory common to most of these studies is the Cushing match-mismatch hypothesis (1969). Based on life-history theory, it postulates that there should be selective pressure for the consumer to \'91match\'92 the timing of the peak of its most energetic phase with that of the timing of its peak resource availability. Given this strong selective pressure, if there is any change to the relative timing of than interaction, there will be a decrease in fitness for the consumer. At the limits, consumer fitness should fall to zero when there is a large enough change to relative timing. 
