\i0 The Cushing hypothesis offers a testable hypothesis for predicting long-term demographic changes in response to climate-change driven shifts in synchrony and has the potential to improve our predictions about these changes. \
\
While the Cushing hypothesis offers a promising theory, the current approach in trophic synchrony has made it difficult to support or refute this hypothesis and move the field forward. Certainly there is some evidence supporting the Cushing hypothesis but the shape and strength of the relationship between consumer fitness and the relative timing of the interaction varies greatly. There are a few key reasons that make it difficult to synthesize the findings across studies to determine if there are any general trends in climate change-driven shifts in synchrony and their consequences. \
\
First, most of these studies do not provide strong tests of the hypothesis, making it difficult to refute the hypothesis if no evidence is found. For example, it can be challenging for a short-term observational study to capture the full range of the fitness or relative timing axis. However, without the complete range of conditions, it is difficult to know the shape of the true relationship. \
\
Second, in many systems, we are lacking an understanding of the basic biological details needed to test this relationship. For example, it is not known whether an increase in the number of days between consumer and resource life history events is actually worse. The Cushing hypothesis assumes that the resource is a major control of consumer dynamics yet this is rarely known in most systems.\
\
Third, most time-series in trophic synchrony studies began in the early 1980s, at the same time as recent climate change. Therefore it is unknown what the pre-climate change baseline should be across most interactions. For applied studies, many confound the pre-climate baseline with the peak of Cushing curve (i.e. peak fitness) and therefore predict that climate change will decrease consumer fitness by changing the relative timing of the interaction. Without knowledge of the pre-climate change baseline, it is difficult to predict the direction and magnitude of fitness consequences due to shifts in synchrony. For fundamental studies that want to understand the underlying processes of consumer-resource dynamics, recognizing that these dynamics are occurring in the context of climate change, our current reality, is key. To this end, an understanding of the system\'92s baseline state is important for providing context and designing studies. The baseline before recent climate change began (early 1980\'92s) will determine whether the current system should be in equilibrium or transient dynamics. If climate change has pushed the system off of baseline, then \
